This is the second of four chapters in Part~\ref{part:sustainability_challenges}
to discuss
areas of life where sustainability challenges are relevant and important.
This chapter covers transportation.
Today, transportation services are provided by cars, trucks, trains, boats, and planes.
Figure~\ref{fig:LLNL_energy_sankey} shows that energy for transportation is 
supplied almost exclusively by liquid petroleum fuels,
because of the high energy densities\index{energy density!liquid fuels} of those fuels
as measured by both energy-to-mass and energy-to-volume ratios.
The U.S.\ transportation sector emits more carbon than any other, 
\Sexpr{US_CO2_by_sector %>% 
dplyr::filter(Sector == "Transportation") %>% 
magrittr::extract2("Proportion [\\%]") %>% 
round(1)}~\% 
of all U.S.\ CO$_2$ emissions.
(See Table~\ref{tab:corrected_co2_emissions}.)
In addition, transportation CO$_2$ emissions are linked to other sectors.
For example, household location (Chapter~\ref{chap:households}) 
determines commuting distances and therefore CO$_2$ emissions for
trips to work, school, church, and shops.

This chapter, and the two following chapters, consider the many ways in which
physical location, economic activity, energy, and resources are interrelated.
This chapter begins by discussing
demand for transportation services and
drivers for that demand.
Thereafter, sustainability challenges for transportation are explained.
Next, options for a sustainability transition are explored.
A summary concludes.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Demand for transportation services}
\label{sec:transportation_demand}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Modern life requires transportation services\index{services!transportation}:
people need to move long and short distances for work and pleasure, and
goods must be shipped from far and near to satisfy human wants and needs.
Transport service demand levels are usually quantified in
passenger-km and tonne-km for personal and freight transport, respectively.
Provision of U.S.\ transportation services by various modes of travel
is shown in Figures~\ref{fig:passengerkm_by_mode}
and~\ref{fig:tonnekm_by_mode}.
Figure~\ref{fig:passengerkm_by_mode} shows that 
passenger transport demand is fulfilled almost exclusively by ``Highway,''
meaning automobiles travelling on roads.
In contrast, Figure~\ref{fig:tonnekm_by_mode} shows that 
freight transport demand is satisfied by a variety of modes.


